Some interesting resources on the web of an introductory level. Made it years ago after weeks of searching out sites. I've updated it a few times over that time. The projects feasibility is hardly questioned at all. The problems are more political than engineering. Therefore the question arises whether all nations capable of building such technology face the same hurdles. The US is still interested in Orion for strictly space usage. It is the most powerful engine possible with todays technology. It's launch capacity is nothing short of incredible and there is no guarantee other nations will ignore it. China and Russia are less nuclearphobic for example.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 299<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/18/02 9:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=219.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/nimoy.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: ORION CRAFT</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; is this thread on who's going to build it just hypothetical<br>
